MongoCursor's constructor has legacy handling for projections (i.e. the {{$fields}} argument) where it attempts to convert {{['x', 'y', 'z']}} into a BSON object (i.e. associative array). This conflicts with the following legitimate use case:

{code}
$collection->find(['_id' => 1], ['22' => 1]);
{code}

This prompts the current code to throw an exception claiming that "field names must be strings", since it assumes integer {{1}} (or perhaps a boolean) is a field name when it attempts to convert {{['22' => 1]}} into {{['1' => 1]}}. Nevermind the fact that it ignores the actual field name "22" in the process.

This legacy behavior is no longer documented (I'm not sure if it ever was), but the code responsible dates back to 0.9.4: https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-php-driver/commit/a10155b298f7723e25cacebbec1f9edd00cb97f0#diff-1588f9459d09323feff65987af110483R83

The exception in question was added in 1.0.8: https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-php-driver/commit/0b5f96abc22e0d73a900a58013b94b2fe77b8aea#diff-1588f9459d09323feff65987af110483R121

An obvious work-around for the above is to cast the projection argument to a stdClass with {{(object)}}. We can go a step further and check if the projection is a numeric array before continuing with the legacy behavior. I will leave a comment in the code that this legacy behavior should be deprecated/removed in due time, but I don't think we should start throwing a deprecation notice in a 1.5.x patch release.

A user on mongodb-users@ reported this, see https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/mongodb-user/dtpCufbo4Os


